%reservation wage.  If it were low enough, some firm would hit
%itThere could not be unemployment, simply because any person
%willing to work would be able to do so, simply by lowering the
%reservation wage enough.

One of the reasons labor markets don't work this way is that
government policies and local institutions {\it distort\/} the way
they function. Examples include minimum wages, restrictions on
wage adjustments, labor unions, limits on hiring and firing, and
so on. We don't argue that these things are bad --- they may very
well have benefits --- but they do have an impact on how the labor
market works.

The minimum wage is the simplest distortion to study.  If we
prohibit purchases of labor services below a given wage, how does
the market operate?
