One of the roles of financial markets is to promote the
reallocation of capital to more productive uses. There's mounting
evidence that countries whose financial markets better accomplish
this task also perform better. Similarly, there is ample data
showing that the ability of an economy to reallocate jobs across
firms, industries, and geographical areas, as well as the ability
to reallocate workers, is critical to its success. Sometimes labor
market institutions are an obstacle to this reallocation process,
and can have unwanted negative effects on macroeconomic
performance.

Consider an example from Europe. In recent years, the European
airline market has gone through a deregulation process that
resembles the one that characterized the US in the 1980s. Before
deregulation, every European country had its own national airline.
The airline was typically a monopolist on internal routes, and a
(collusive) duopolist (with the other country's airline) on
international routes.  Like most monopolists, these airlines
charged high fares and operated inefficiently.  Now any company
can fly any route in the European Union. The entry of new carriers
(in particular the no-frill Southwest imitators) meant big trouble
for many of the incumbents. Sabena and Swissair went bust. Others
(Alitalia?) will probably follow suit. It is clear that at the end
of the reorganization of the industry, fares will be much lower
(they are already, as a matter of fact). As a result, people will
fly more often and there will be more jobs in the industry. Along
the way, job destruction by the incumbents will be accompanied by
(greater) job creation by the new entrants.

Who gains? Consumers and workers in new firms. Who loses?
Incumbent firms' workers and shareholders.  Standard analysis of
the costs of monopoly tell us that the gains are greater than the
losses, but the political process does not necessarily weight them
equally. In the EU, the speed of adjustment, and even the new
structure of the industry, depend in large part on employment
protection laws. These laws impose high severance costs and often
give unions greater influence in such decisions, with the effect
of reducing the speed of both job destruction (out with the old)
and job creation (in with the new).

The bottom line: laws that ``protect'' jobs often have the effect
of making job creation less attractive. Even if they reduce the
rate of job destruction, as intended, they may ultimately reduce
the number of jobs available. Moreover, they inhibit the economy's
ability to reallocate labor to more productive uses. The impact on
aggregate performance can be large.

